WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.061 --> 00:00:02.478
(soft music)

2
00:00:08.370 --> 00:00:09.930
<v Instructor>Good morning everyone.</v>

3
00:00:09.930 --> 00:00:12.073
So we're gonna switch gears a little bit

4
00:00:12.073 --> 00:00:14.220
to talk about endocrine disorders.

5
00:00:14.220 --> 00:00:16.110
As you know, there are a number of endocrine disorders,

6
00:00:16.110 --> 00:00:17.940
so we're gonna try to hit the highlights

7
00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:21.150
and focus mostly on the thyroid,

8
00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:23.610
thyroid parathyroid,

9
00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.980
and then we'll take a look at some cushings

10
00:00:25.980 --> 00:00:27.340
and some Addisons

11
00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:32.253
and how to work up masses, which is a common board question.

12
00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:35.013
So let's start with a question.

13
00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:39.450
This is a 17-year-old who has neck swelling

14
00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:41.820
for two to three weeks, five pound weight gain

15
00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:44.070
and feels increasingly tired.

16
00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:46.590
Otherwise, no additional symptoms.

17
00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:49.110
The exam is significant for diffusely, enlarged,

18
00:00:49.110 --> 00:00:51.780
smooth and non-tender thyroid.

19
00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:53.880
So what do you do first?

20
00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:56.223
You get a T4 or reverse T3,

21
00:00:57.569 --> 00:00:58.402
a TSH,

22
00:00:59.862 --> 00:01:01.473
or a thyroid ultrasound.

23
00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:08.430
Good, good, good.

24
00:01:08.430 --> 00:01:09.840
Most of us got this right.

25
00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:13.260
So the workup, just as a rule,

26
00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:15.150
the initial diagnostic step

27
00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:19.770
for any thyroid disorder will always be TSH.

28
00:01:19.770 --> 00:01:21.870
It will never be a reverse T3.

29
00:01:21.870 --> 00:01:23.940
In fact, the reverse T3 will probably never be

30
00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:25.800
asked on a test.

31
00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:27.570
It will be a TSH.

32
00:01:27.570 --> 00:01:29.010
That's always, whether you're looking

33
00:01:29.010 --> 00:01:31.740
at hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism,

34
00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:34.504
TSH will always be your initial intersection

35
00:01:34.504 --> 00:01:36.960
for beginning your diagnostic journey.

36
00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:37.793
So here's your,

37
00:01:37.793 --> 00:01:42.390
our spectrum from hypothyroidism to hyperthyroidism,

38
00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:45.780
and then we have this ambiguous zone in the middle,

39
00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:49.017
which is the subclinical hypothyroidism,

40
00:01:49.017 --> 00:01:51.750
and we'll talk about that briefly.

41
00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:54.540
So this patient is another younger person,

42
00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:58.740
a 20-year-old who comes in for a routine Suboxone refill

43
00:01:58.740 --> 00:02:02.310
and has no cardiovascular risk factors other than obesity.

44
00:02:02.310 --> 00:02:05.250
He's been tired and has had some weight gain

45
00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:08.610
and wants you to check his thyroid and his testosterone.

46
00:02:08.610 --> 00:02:11.250
His TSH comes back at 9.1.

47
00:02:11.250 --> 00:02:13.500
His free T4 is normal,

48
00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:16.740
and his testosterone is 401.

49
00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:19.563
What is the next appropriate step?

50
00:02:21.810 --> 00:02:24.663
Do you start him on treatment with TSH?

51
00:02:26.280 --> 00:02:28.623
Do you encourage a Mediterranean diet?

52
00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:34.680
Do you watch and wait and then consider repeating?

53
00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:37.353
Where do you check thyroid antibody studies?

54
00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:43.673
Good.

55
00:02:43.673 --> 00:02:45.210
Most of us got this, the opportunity

56
00:02:45.210 --> 00:02:48.142
to learn here, again,

57
00:02:48.142 --> 00:02:49.310
what is the testosterone of 401?

58
00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:51.840
Do you treat a testosterone of 401?

59
00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:53.910
No, good.

60
00:02:53.910 --> 00:02:55.230
So this is,

61
00:02:55.230 --> 00:02:57.810
puts us in the zone of what might be considered

62
00:02:57.810 --> 00:03:00.090
a subclinical hypothyroidism.

63
00:03:00.090 --> 00:03:02.540
So this patient is symptomatic.

64
00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:04.350
He could be symptomatic from a number of things,

65
00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:08.700
but he's symptomatic and has a TSH of 9.1.

66
00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:12.690
Now, not every person is symptomatic with a TSH of 9.1.

67
00:03:12.690 --> 00:03:16.230
If you are in the geriatric spectrum of life

68
00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:20.460
and you have a TSH of 9.1, you may not be symptomatic at all

69
00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:25.050
because it's very common for TSHs to be elevated up

70
00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:28.650
to 7.5 or eight, if you're 70 or above.

71
00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:30.660
It's not the situation when this patient,

72
00:03:30.660 --> 00:03:32.490
look for your symptoms.

73
00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:35.290
If your TSH is greater than 10

74
00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:41.510
and you're somewhat symptomatic, you can still treat that.

75
00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:43.920
If you have a TSH greater than 10

76
00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:47.070
and you have TPO antibodies that are positive,

77
00:03:47.070 --> 00:03:51.030
TPO antibodies tell you that there's a greater likelihood

78
00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:55.140
of moving from, even if you have a TSH of say eight,

79
00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:57.540
or you're pregnant and you have a TSH

80
00:03:57.540 --> 00:03:58.980
that's slightly elevated.

81
00:03:58.980 --> 00:04:01.590
Anytime you have TPO antibodies,

82
00:04:01.590 --> 00:04:04.140
that indicates that you have a greater likelihood

83
00:04:04.140 --> 00:04:06.840
of one day becoming hypothyroid

84
00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:10.473
and that would require increased vigilance and surveillance.

85
00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:12.540
Be careful though,

86
00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:15.753
if we overtreat subclinical hypothyroidism,

87
00:04:16.863 --> 00:04:19.230
there's always a risk for AFib and osteoporosis.

88
00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:22.170
So that's a good test question right there.

89
00:04:22.170 --> 00:04:23.620
Risk of overtreating

90
00:04:24.756 --> 00:04:27.420
or super therapeutic TSHs

91
00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:30.390
with super therapeutic levothyroxine bears the risk

92
00:04:30.390 --> 00:04:31.893
of osteoporosis and AFib.

93
00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:38.343
Interestingly, not everybody feels better if you treat them.

94
00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:40.950
So there's lots of data that shows

95
00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:43.800
that treatment does not always improve

96
00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:47.850
in addition to symptoms, survival and morbidity.

97
00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:51.061
There is, however, a slightly increased risk

98
00:04:51.061 --> 00:04:52.330
of cardiovascular disease

99
00:04:53.262 --> 00:04:54.840
if you have subclinical hypothyroidism.

100
00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:57.303
So I think most of us tend to treat that overall.

101
00:04:58.890 --> 00:05:01.890
So hypothyroidism is very common.

102
00:05:01.890 --> 00:05:04.830
Females greater than males, six to one.

103
00:05:04.830 --> 00:05:07.230
There are a variety of reasons for it.

104
00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:09.750
The most important ones are the primary ones.

105
00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:12.810
So these are your

106
00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:14.910
autoimmune thyroiditis

107
00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:16.200
such as Hashimoto's,

108
00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:18.120
which will be the most common one,

109
00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:20.220
ablations, etcetera.

110
00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:23.520
Other secondary ones that are good to remember,

111
00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:25.260
especially the medications.

112
00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:30.010
Lithium and amiodarone are the two big ones that pop up

113
00:05:30.010 --> 00:05:30.993
on board questions.

114
00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:34.020
If you recall, amiodarone is,

115
00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:35.220
has a double-edged sword

116
00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:38.260
because it can cause both hypothyroidism

117
00:05:39.767 --> 00:05:40.600
and hyperthyroidism.

118
00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:43.830
So it has that duality of it.

119
00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:45.930
And then there are the transient,

120
00:05:45.930 --> 00:05:49.470
mostly viral induced subacute thyroiditis

121
00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:50.880
that we'll talk about.

122
00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:52.830
And then there can be problems in the brain

123
00:05:52.830 --> 00:05:56.130
in your central access that can contribute.

124
00:05:56.130 --> 00:05:57.380
In your pituitary gland.

125
00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:59.910
We will come back to that in just a little bit.

126
00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:01.322
So here are the classic factors

127
00:06:01.322 --> 00:06:03.573
that contribute to hypothyroidism.

128
00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:06.630
We already talked about the female sex being,

129
00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:08.610
having increased risk.

130
00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:11.430
Growing old brings you increased risk.

131
00:06:11.430 --> 00:06:15.030
Caucasians Type 1 diabetes, down syndrome,

132
00:06:15.030 --> 00:06:17.031
and if you have a family history,

133
00:06:17.031 --> 00:06:19.470
that will always put you at a greater risk.

134
00:06:19.470 --> 00:06:21.960
If you've had a previous episode or radiation,

135
00:06:21.960 --> 00:06:23.973
that also brings greater risk.

136
00:06:25.650 --> 00:06:29.620
These are the classic symptoms as in this case

137
00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:32.910
that I think we're all pretty familiar with.

138
00:06:32.910 --> 00:06:36.270
Interesting to think about the myalgias, which can come.

139
00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:38.550
How many of you're checking your deep tendon reflexes

140
00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:41.070
if you're concerned about hypothyroidism.

141
00:06:41.070 --> 00:06:43.500
That's a good physical exam finding to turn back

142
00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:48.420
to depression and bradycardia and the coarse hair.

143
00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:50.073
These are classic symptoms.

144
00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:53.490
So how do we diagnose?

145
00:06:53.490 --> 00:06:56.730
And I feel like this is a great place to refresh

146
00:06:56.730 --> 00:07:00.123
what we do when we're starting our diagnostic pathway.

147
00:07:01.801 --> 00:07:04.920
TSH, TSH, will always be your initial, so you don't need

148
00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:08.040
to check a T4, T3, someone comes in,

149
00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:09.780
they're symptomatic, they have two

150
00:07:09.780 --> 00:07:13.080
or three of these symptoms and you wanna start the process.

151
00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:17.130
So you're gonna get a TSH first, not a TSH

152
00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:19.590
and a T4 and a T3

153
00:07:19.590 --> 00:07:20.710
or a TPO

154
00:07:21.985 --> 00:07:25.230
or a thyroid globulin receptor antibody.

155
00:07:25.230 --> 00:07:27.120
You're just gonna get a TSH.

156
00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:30.900
If the TSH comes back and it's elevated.

157
00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:34.860
So a normal TSH is like 0.5 to five.

158
00:07:34.860 --> 00:07:37.860
If your TSH is elevated, then you,

159
00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:39.690
you would consider getting a T4.

160
00:07:39.690 --> 00:07:42.360
You do not need to get a T3 initially,

161
00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:43.710
but you could get a T4

162
00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:47.283
and a TSH just to reinforce that diagnosis.

163
00:07:48.300 --> 00:07:50.460
The thyroid antibody studies,

164
00:07:50.460 --> 00:07:54.706
that will be more important if you're thinking about either

165
00:07:54.706 --> 00:07:55.940
Graves or Hashimoto's.

166
00:07:55.940 --> 00:07:57.990
So we'll come back and speak about

167
00:07:57.990 --> 00:08:00.390
that a little bit, in a moment.

168
00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:01.770
There are some other surrogate markers

169
00:08:01.770 --> 00:08:04.830
to remind yourself of, especially lipids.

170
00:08:04.830 --> 00:08:08.553
You can have anemia associated with hypothyroidism.

171
00:08:09.840 --> 00:08:12.480
The thyroid hormone is very important in terms

172
00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:16.623
of the metabolism of producing hemoglobin.

173
00:08:17.555 --> 00:08:19.593
So you can commonly see anemias.

174
00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:25.680
So you decide to start therapy and six weeks later you,

175
00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:29.223
after starting levothyroxine, you check a steady state TSH.

176
00:08:30.123 --> 00:08:31.080
So that's when you do it.

177
00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:35.550
The TSH decreased from 9.3 to 7.2.

178
00:08:35.550 --> 00:08:38.430
All of the following factors are barriers

179
00:08:38.430 --> 00:08:42.030
to reaching a therapeutic TSH except treating

180
00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:44.220
with desiccated thyroid supplementation.

181
00:08:44.220 --> 00:08:46.260
So that would be like armor.

182
00:08:46.260 --> 00:08:48.513
Treating with T4 rather than T3.

183
00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:52.110
Patient is also taking lithium.

184
00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:56.733
Patient is taking iron sulfate for iron deficiency already.

185
00:08:58.293 --> 00:09:00.513
So which of these is not a barrier?

186
00:09:06.090 --> 00:09:07.560
Excellent, most of us got this right.

187
00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:08.910
Let's take a look at these.

188
00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:15.060
So why do we not treat in general with,

189
00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:16.860
this is a question that always comes up.

190
00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:20.599
Why do we not treat in general with T4

191
00:09:20.599 --> 00:09:22.200
and T3 or armour?

192
00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:23.033
You can do that in two ways.

193
00:09:23.033 --> 00:09:23.866
You can treat with armour,

194
00:09:23.866 --> 00:09:25.410
which is ground up pick thyroid,

195
00:09:25.410 --> 00:09:29.340
or you can treat with synthetic T4 or synthetic T3.

196
00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:30.570
That's cytomel.

197
00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:31.680
Why do we not do that?

198
00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:34.083
It's not recommended to do that.

199
00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:37.710
Well, if you think about the physiology of what happens

200
00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:39.240
with T4 and T3.

201
00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:42.870
T4 is the vast majority of the product

202
00:09:42.870 --> 00:09:44.820
that comes from the thyroids.

203
00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:46.050
Vast majority.

204
00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:48.540
T4 lasts for a week.

205
00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:50.670
It's half life is seven days.

206
00:09:50.670 --> 00:09:53.940
The half-life of T3 sticks around for like five

207
00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:55.530
to six hours.

208
00:09:55.530 --> 00:09:58.490
So the, what happens, the reason why we treat with T4

209
00:09:58.490 --> 00:10:00.840
is because T4 is the molecule

210
00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:02.160
that's doing most of the work.

211
00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:03.990
So it interacts with whatever cell,

212
00:10:03.990 --> 00:10:05.760
all cells in the body.

213
00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:07.410
Interacts with the cell.

214
00:10:07.410 --> 00:10:10.680
T4 gets delineated, it becomes T3.

215
00:10:10.680 --> 00:10:13.950
We think about the T3 as the activated molecule,

216
00:10:13.950 --> 00:10:17.430
but it's actually the conversion of T4

217
00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:20.970
to T3 at the membrane that makes that

218
00:10:20.970 --> 00:10:22.860
that metabolic magic happen.

219
00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:25.710
So the T4 is vastly more important than the T3

220
00:10:25.710 --> 00:10:27.240
in terms of supplementation.

221
00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:30.930
You'll sometimes see the psychiatrist who will add T3

222
00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:33.870
to patients who have refractory depression.

223
00:10:33.870 --> 00:10:36.630
There's some data for that, but not great data,

224
00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:38.160
but there is no great data

225
00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:40.533
for routinely treating T4, T3.

226
00:10:41.677 --> 00:10:44.973
That's a a question that always comes up.

227
00:10:45.990 --> 00:10:48.122
You can, however,

228
00:10:48.122 --> 00:10:51.570
and you may have patients out there who have a TSH

229
00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:54.870
that you normalize with with synthetic T4,

230
00:10:54.870 --> 00:10:56.880
but they still feel terrible.

231
00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:59.010
So in those patients you can consider,

232
00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:00.840
and those patients might be folks

233
00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:02.250
who've either had an ablation.

234
00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:03.330
They've either had surgery

235
00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:04.830
to remove their thyroid.

236
00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:08.460
They've either had a history of Hashimoto's.

237
00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:12.150
Those people you can consider in certain circumstances

238
00:11:12.150 --> 00:11:13.620
to give them T3 and T4.

239
00:11:13.620 --> 00:11:16.200
But in general, just T4.

240
00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:18.150
When you do start your therapy,

241
00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:21.423
the typical loading dose is 1.6 mcg per kilo.

242
00:11:22.475 --> 00:11:23.361
For a younger person

243
00:11:23.361 --> 00:11:24.870
and an older person, you start at a lower dose.

244
00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:26.550
You start at one.

245
00:11:26.550 --> 00:11:29.190
Generally you recommend taking on a fasting stomach

246
00:11:29.190 --> 00:11:32.100
and waiting 30 to 60 minutes before eating

247
00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:36.180
and then you always check steady state is five to six weeks.

248
00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:38.853
So it's not helpful to check before that time.

249
00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:45.120
Again, don't use armour, don't use combination therapy.

250
00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:46.890
You can come back and review this.

251
00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:49.690
There are a lot of other things that contribute

252
00:11:51.375 --> 00:11:54.000
to the dysregulation of the thyroid.

253
00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.860
We'll talk about some of those right now,

254
00:11:55.860 --> 00:11:59.130
but in general, you can push a little bit lower if your

255
00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:02.103
patient's not feeling well to three or 2.5.

256
00:12:03.420 --> 00:12:08.369
But there can be problems with the conversion of T4 to T3

257
00:12:08.369 --> 00:12:10.950
so that the physiology of this,

258
00:12:10.950 --> 00:12:15.570
the metabolism of the thyroid gland is exquisitely

259
00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:18.420
detailed and it's much bigger than

260
00:12:18.420 --> 00:12:20.580
what we think about it because there are all these things

261
00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:23.730
that can contribute to the different enzymes,

262
00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:26.853
the dyonisus, the antibody binding,

263
00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:29.700
the liver metabolism of all these things.

264
00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:33.300
But you can have deficiencies in these things,

265
00:12:33.300 --> 00:12:36.630
selenium, notably and other vitamins.

266
00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:38.850
A vitamins, the B vitamins,

267
00:12:38.850 --> 00:12:41.550
